1 WHEREAS, many communities across the United States have successfully
2 implemented consolidated solid waste authorities or regional service districts that provide
3 one-stop shop solutions for routine trash service, disaster debris response, recycling, landfill
4 operations, and mitigation planning; and
5 WHEREAS, a unified parish-wide approach could strengthen emergency
6 preparedness, improve FEMA reimbursement compliance, create economies of scale, and
7 allow for long-term infrastructure investments such as debris staging areas, transfer stations,
8 recycling centers, and hardened landfill facilities; and
9 WHEREAS, resilient waste and debris management systems are a critical component
10 of public health, environmental protection, economic recovery, and infrastructure stability
11 during and after disasters.
12 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
13 Legislature of Louisiana does hereby urge and request the Department of Environmental
14 Quality, the Governor's Office of Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness, the
15 Ouachita Parish Police Jury, and all incorporated municipalities within Ouachita Parish to
16 collaboratively conduct a comprehensive study to address parish-wide consolidation of
17 services, disaster debris management and FEMA compliance, resiliency and infrastructure
18 improvements, and governance and funding models.
19 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the study of consolidation of services shall
20 include consideration of the following:
21 (1) Centralized residential and commercial trash collection.
22 (2) Parish-wide debris hauling and disposal contracts.
23 (3) Unified billing and service administration models.
24 (4) Cost savings and rate stabilization impacts.
25 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the study of disaster debris management and
26 FEMA compliance shall include consideration of the following:
27 (1) Pre-event debris removal contracts.
28 (2) Designated debris management and staging sites.
29 (3) FEMA documentation protocols.
30 (4) Rapid deployment cleanup frameworks.
